reviewText: I have seen the other reviews and the comments about the poor video quality. I can't completely disagree. I think the band gave a great performance, it just wasn't captured as best as it could be. The fact that this version came with a bonus CD is what made the purchase worth it for me. If I happen to see a new Europe CD alone I probably would have not picked it up, but after hearing Start From The Dark, I was amazed at what a great CD they created. Europe did a A+ piece of work, which seems to be tough for bands to do. Many bands that were enjoying their biggest years a decade or two ago never seem to be able to make a new Cd with the same "impact" as their "glory days" work. Europe made a CD that I would consider one of their best offerings, and the 2 DVD set is a pure bonus

reviewText: I was with much joy to know that the band that I had been listening to since my schooldays have finally release their live performance on DVD.Based on the reviews, it sounded like the cameraman, the lighting man the editing and mastering staffs ought to be given a kick in their a** for spoiling the whole concert.... except for the sound engineer and the mixing crew.I thought of buying this DVD..but...I decided not too.I guess that's why the concert is name Live from the DARK...man..what's wrong with more lights...
summary: The band Europe is good..but who hired the cameramans

reviewText: I agree with the other reviewer regarding the video quality on this DVD. It is irrefutably one of the worst video qualities I have ever seen. I believe this is because the concert was shot in poor lighting. Aside from this, Europe's performance was brilliant, outstanding, powerful and flawless. Audio quality is much better if not flawless. Joe Tempest's vocals was awesome, he is a great vocalist, but by far the best performance was offered by a true guitar hero John Norum. Keep an eye on Norum's unbelievable solo on Superstitious. I like the old songs better than the new ones even though the new ones are solid as well. There is really not much more to say except the fact that Europe is back and the band is here to stay, no doubt about that! In my view, Europe is one of the best rock bands in the world, certainly without a doubt the best band ever to have come out of Sweden. I would have given this DVD five stars easily had it not been for the poor video quality. But for a true Europe fan this does not make any difference, it is a must have. BUY!

reviewText: Fans of the Swedish rock band Europe, the most commercially successful band from Scandinavia, should appreciate Live From The Dark (2006), a two disc set that marks the reunion of the classic "Final Countdown" lineup.  The band consisting of Joey Tempest (vocals), John Norum (guitar), John Leven (bass), Ian Haugland (drums), and Mic Michaeli (keyboards), reformed in 2003, after being on hiatus for many years.  Disc One contains a full length, 100 minute performance recorded at Carling Apollo Hammersmith Theater, London, the final show of their 2005 Start From The Dark tour.  The second disk contains a number of bonus features, including interviews, music videos, sound checks, a featurette of the tour, and various video clips.  "Taxi Diaries" is a series of very candid and informative interviews, shot while various members of the band are travelling in the back seat of a taxi.The live performance contains 18 songs, spanning the band's career up to this point.  John Norum left Europe in 1986, and the band recorded Out Of This World (1988), and Prisoners In Paradise (1991), with Kee Marcello on guitar.  When the band reformed in 2003, Marcello was in his own band, and declined an offer to rejoin.  The talented Norum, does a fine job of covering songs from the Marcello period, including Superstitious, Ready or Not, Let The Good Times Rock, Sign Of The Times, and Girl From Lebanon.  Actively supporting their 2004 release, Start From The Dark, the setlist includes, Got To Have Faith, America, Wake Up Call, Flames, Hero, and Start From The Dark.  In general, except for the ballad Hero, the newer material has more of a harder edge, with plenty of crunching guitar.  Of course, Europe is probably most recognized for the song The Final Countdown, and the hits from their 1986 breakthrough album.  The band ends the show with The Final Countdown, while Rock The Night, Cherokee, and Carrie are featured at the tail end of the set.The concert production features good coverage of the band, with a nice selection of camera angles.  The video is not true 16:9 widescreen.  Quality is generally good, but not great, as grain is evident, especially at 1080p.  Europe are mostly steady rockers, who aside from Joey Tempest, don't do a lot of moving around on stage.  It does not appear that his voice has lost anything, as Tempest sounds great, wielding his trademark white mike stand.  The concert and the ample number of extras, make for a nice package, which should please most casual fans.  Hardcore fans interested in seeing the same classic lineup in their youth, may want to check out their concert DVD, Europe: The Final Countdown Tour - Live In Sweden 1986 (2006).
